<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Principles on Learn, Converse, Share</title><link>http://jmeridth.com/tags/principles/</link><description>Recent content in Principles on Learn, Converse, Share</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Wed, 10 Jan 2007 00:46:00 -0600</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="http://jmeridth.com/tags/principles/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Law of Demeter (Principle of Least Knowledge)</title><link>http://jmeridth.com/posts/law-of-demeter-principle-of-least-knowledge/</link><pubDate>Wed, 10 Jan 2007 00:46:00 -0600</pubDate><guid>http://jmeridth.com/posts/law-of-demeter-principle-of-least-knowledge/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;I was reading up on the Law of Demeter again after reading &lt;a href="http://codebetter.com/blogs/jeremy.miller/archive/2007/01/08/Orthogonal-Code.aspx" class="external-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener"&gt;Jeremy Miller&amp;rsquo;s post about orthogonality&lt;/a&gt; (good post by the way).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Law of Demeter&lt;/strong&gt; (LoD from now on) was created at NorthEastern University, Boston in 1987 while a team was working on the Demeter project.
LoD dictates that object A, when calling object B should call a service on object C through B.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bad (Common):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-csharp" data-lang="csharp"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;inventory&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;SalesInfo&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;Items&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;Count&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="m"&gt;2500&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Good:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-csharp" data-lang="csharp"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;SalesInfo&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;si&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;inventory&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;SalesInfo&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="kt"&gt;int&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;salesItemsCount&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;si&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;GetSalesItemsCount&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;();&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;[granted this might possibly be a violation of Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)  - Thanks Josh (Joshua Lockwood)]&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>